I wish, with all my heart, that every person on earth could experience a few days like this! My brother, who has autism and severe epilepsy, competed in the Special Olympics State Games as a bowler this weekend, and I went to volunteer. Super proud of Tristan and his doubles partner, Morgan, for doing their best and placing 4th- but this weekend has been SO MUCH MORE than that. Some of the bowlers are legally blind or can barely stand and are still out there, giving it their best - that takes immense courage. At the Hawaiian dance, I’m not sure I’ve ever seen so many beaming faces dancing so enthusiastically, like nobody was watching (because honestly, life’s too short to care if they are) - that is pure joy. When your opponent throws a gutter ball, you encourage them for the strike - that is true kindness. Inspiring doesn’t even feel like an adequate word for how amazing this weekend was - so thankful for Special Olympics and all they do for those with special needs and so proud of everyone who competed! ❤️

Today is PREMIERE DAY for “Haunting of the Queen Mary” and the soundtrack! Link in my bio to listen to my new music available through @lakeshorerecords 💛

Incredibly surreal experience to be in the theater, seeing (and hearing) myself on the big screen for the first time! And it was extra special to be sitting together alongside our brilliant music team, watching all our hard work come to life.
The music in this film was as intricate as the story itself. The film itself is so amazingly unique - an artistic, avant-garde horror, playing the line between historical reality and psychological terror, between the beautiful and the grotesque - that the music had to be just as unique. For this film, I’ve created and performed everything from pop murder ballads to country crossovers to 1930s style big band numbers. It’s been such an amazing experience working with @jasonlivesay @nolanlivesay @ryanomusic in writing and performing the big band numbers for the 1930s scenes, and I’m so glad we all got to see it together!
Check out the soundtrack now at the link in my bio 🖤

18 Octobers ago, Pumpkin jumped into the back of our car and found a home - and now, I can’t imagine what coming home from being on the road will be like without my furry little bestie. I genuinely believe all cats go to heaven, but especially ones like Pumpkin. She was a fierce little thing, but boy did she love us fiercely too. Any time I cried as a kid, she was right there, and I’d sing and pet her until whatever it was didn’t seem so bad anymore. When my epileptic brother had a seizure, she was always right there when he woke up, anxious to see that he was okay. She was the first to stand on my Bible or jump up on my desk as I worked and was the best (and quietest!) studio cat ever. We grew up together, and she was there for me and my family in every way a cat can be. But this week, I came home and found her hardly able to move - and in her last few days, all she wanted was to be near us, for us to hold her paw, to love on her. And I sure hope she felt all the love and comfort in the world. We love you Pumpkin - thanks for being the best childhood cat a girl could ask for. Miss you already and thankful I’ll see you again someday ❤️ [SWIPE for a 2011 throwback]

“Can’t Save You” is such a personal song. Like so many of you, I found myself in a situation with someone who was controlling and manipulative, gaslighting me into believing that I was to blame for their anger, jealousy, and instability. I wrote “Can’t Save You” a few years ago, in the moment of realization of what had been true all along. It is never your responsibility to save someone else from themselves or their inner demons. I set the release of this song and hope it gives strength to any of you who are out there struggling to free yourself from the weight of such a heavy situation.

400 years ago this fall, my 8th great grandad, Edward Doty, who had landed in Plymouth on the Mayflower, took a seat at the first ever American Thanksgiving. This year, like every year, I’m so thankful for his sacrifice and take the day to consider what it must have been like. An indentured servant, he sailed here in hopes he’d find opportunity for a better life and religious freedom. Despite being the first man punished for dueling in the colony, he grew to become a prominent businessman and landowner, but not without risking everything. When my ancestor signed the Mayflower Compact, the first document of self-governance in what would become the United States, he and the other men on board committed treason against the King of England, and at risk of death, they established the democratic foundation of America. 
As we all celebrate around our Thanksgiving tables, I think that symbolically, it’s an opportunity to be thankful for the things in our lives worth “signing our names” under. God, friends and family, freedom, and the pursuit of happiness - I’m glad that 400 years later, the same things that drove Edward to Plymouth still mean so much to me and my family. And I sure hope, wherever you are today, you have a most blessed Thanksgiving with the ones you’re thankful for ❤️

Christmas Eve is one of my favorite days each year because of what it represents - the ultimate hope. As children all over the world go to sleep tonight in anticipation, I can’t help but think about the anticipation surrounding the very first Christmas. How God’s people had waited hundreds of years to hear His voice… and in the midst of their waiting, God answered not with the thundering voice of a king, but with the cry of a baby named Jesus. Not from a palace, but from a stable. Christmas is the celebration of God humbling Himself in love to come into our world and bring the ultimate hope for all people. “Behold, the lamb of God, who takes away the sins of the world!” John 1:29
I hope this Christmas Eve you are surrounded by the kind of hope Christ brought that very first Christmas - a hope that pierces through even the darkest of seasons and reaches down in love ❤️

My love of words and writing comes from my Grammy, and over the past 40 years or so, she has slowly been compiling chapters of her life’s story and dreaming of becoming a published author. So in the past few months, my mom and I quietly worked on editing and preparing her memoir, The Patent Leather Purse, for publishing. The look on her face opening it says it all - this Christmas was an extra special one, and after 7 decades, it’s been the coolest thing to be part of my grandmother’s dream of being a published author. Also thankful for my amazing mother, who had this perfect idea and made it all possible!

Christmas with Grandpa! 80 Christmases in to this wonderful journey and he’s still going strong as ever so we surprised him with a fun cookie cake to celebrate his Psalm 90:10 year!! From the funny Christmas outfits to the guns, Grandpa sure knows how to have a great time for the holidays and I’m so thankful for all the time we get to spend together 🙌
